#############################
########Pre-requisites#######
#############################

	  Python 3.6+
	  Node.js 12
	  Redis 5                                       (caching and realtime updates)
	  MariaDB 10.3.x / Postgres 9.5.x               (to run database driven apps)
	  yarn 1.12+                                    (js dependency manager)
	  pip 20+                                       (py dependency manager)
	  wkhtmltopdf (version 0.12.5 with patched qt)  (for pdf generation)
	  cron                                          (bench's scheduled jobs: automated certificate renewal, scheduled backups)
	  NGINX                                         (proxying multitenant sites in production)


############################
#####Installation###########
############################

### STEP 1 Install git
	
	sudo apt-get install git

### STEP 2 The python-dev package installation python-dev contains the header files you need to build Python extensions.

install Python 2.7.X dev package

	sudo apt-get install python-dev

OR
	
install Python 3.X dev package 

	sudo apt-get install python3-dev

### STEP 3 Install setuptools and pip (Python's Package Manager).
Setuptools allow developers to more easily build and distribute Python packages, especially ones that have dependencies on other packages.
pip is a package manager for Python. it's a tool that allows you to install and manage additional libraries and dependencies

install Python 2.7.X 

	sudo apt-get install python-setuptools python-pip

OR

install Python 3.X 

	sudo apt-get install python3-setuptools python3-pip

### STEP 4 Install virtualenv:
virtualenv is used to manage Python packages for different projects. 
virtualenv allows you to avoid installing Python packages globally which could break system tools or other projects.
	
	sudo apt-get install virtualenv

### STEP 5 Create an alias for pip and python to enforce use of python 3

	alias python=python3
	alias pip=pip3

### STEP 6 Install MariaDB 10.3 stable package

	sudo apt update
	sudo aptitude install mariadb-server

IMPORTENT:During this installation you'll be prompted to set the MySQL root password.If you are not prompted for the same You can initialize the MySQL server setup by executing the following command
	
	sudo mysql_secure_installation
	
	 
### STEP 7  MySQL database development files

	sudo apt-get install libmysqlclient-dev

### STEP 8 edit the mariadb configuration

	sudo nano /etc/mysql/my.cnf

add this to the my.cnf file

	[mysqld]
	character-set-client-handshake = FALSE
	character-set-server = utf8mb4
	collation-server = utf8mb4_unicode_ci

	[mysql]
	default-character-set = utf8mb4

Now press (Ctrl-X) to exit

	sudo service mysql restart

### STEP 9 install Redis 
used as a database, cache, and message broker.
	
	sudo apt-get install redis-server

### STEP 10 install Node.js 12.X package
Node.js is an open-source, Javascript runtime environment that lets you effortlessly develop fast and scalable web applications.

	sudo apt-get install curl
	curl -sL https://deb.nodesource.com/setup_12.x | sudo -E bash -
	sudo apt-get install -y nodejs

### STEP 11  yarn as a package manager Yarn is a package manager for JS
	
	sudo npm install -g yarn
	
### STEP 12 PDF generation functionality provided by frappe, you'll need to install wkhtmltopdf
wkhtmltopdf is an open source command line tool to render HTML into PDF format using the Qt WebKit rendering engine.

	wget https://github.com/wkhtmltopdf/packaging/releases/download/0.12.6-1/wkhtmltox_0.12.6-1.bionic_amd64.deb
	sudo apt install ./wkhtmltox_0.12.6-1.bionic_amd64.deb
	rm wkhtmltox_0.12.6-1.bionic_amd64.deb
	
### STEP 13 Create a user

	adduser frappe_user
	usermod -aG sudo frappe_user
	su - frappe_user

### STEP 14 Getting Bench onto your system

	pip3 install frappe-bench

IMPORTENT: you may wish to log out and log back into your terminal before next step and You must login / "su - frappe_user"
	
	bench --version
	





















